Boston, MA
Mr. Wayne Chang is a Co-Founder and serves as Board Member at Digits. He is the Founder and serves as Chief Executive Officer at Patented.ai. He serves as Board Advisor at Tablelist. He also serves as an Advisor at Soma Capital. He serves as Venture Advisor at Impellent Ventures. Previously, He served as Co-Chief Executive Officer at Digits. He is a serial entrepreneur and investor, who's been named one of Forbes' Top 50 Angel Investors and one of 40 Under 40 by Boston Business Journal. His ability to meld psychology and strategy has led to magical product and design experiences that have scaled to more than seven billion devices. He co-founded Crashlytics (acquired by Twitter for over $100 million), co-created Fabric (acquired by Google), and won an Emmy Award as a producer on the environmental documentary Chasing Coral. He is a college dropout who has been awarded an honorary doctorate from his alma mater, the University of Massachusetts Amherst. Throughout his career, he's been involved in over eighty start-ups and thirty-two exits, resulting in over $150 billion of value created.

Mr. Wayne Hu serves as Partner, Venture at SignalFire. He is also an Angel Investor. He also serves as Board Member at Grow Therapy, CourseKey and ScopeAR. He joined SignalFire to help form the initial investment team in 2015, and leads seed stage investments focused on consumer, emerging technology platform shifts, and historically innovation-sparse sectors that can be reinvented end-to-end. Previously, he was one of five consultants at McKinsey & Co a year to receive a Global Institute Fellowship to join MGI, named the top think tank in the world by several top academic institutions for its research on macro forces and technology trends transforming the economys largest sectors. Before joining SignalFire, he was the Global Strategy Lead for YouTube ads monetization, responsible for go-to-market strategy formulation for Googles growing multi-billion-dollar video business. Earlier in his career, he was an operator in the education sector, managing a team responsible for turnaround initiatives within Chicagos public school system before transitioning into working and advising early stage ed tech companies. He received an MBA from Harvard Business School while also working on the investment team at Kleiner Perkins Caufield & Byers, focused on sectors such as transportation, robotics, and marketplaces. He graduated from Princeton University with a B.A in Mathematical Economics, Phi Beta Kappa, where he played on the mens tennis team. He was taught to code by his parents from rural Taiwan who immigrated to the US to become engineers. While his first business selling TI-83 graphing calculator games built in Visual Basic did not pan out, today he lives out his childhood dreams by partnering with early-stage startups that are breaking down barriers to a more connected, open and educated society
